    <subsection>
        <title>The Zero Exponent</title>

        <p>So far, we have been working with natural number (<m>1</m>, <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, ...) exponents. To understand how <m>0</m> should behave as an exponent, let's consider the pattern of decreasing powers of <m>2</m> below.</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>power</cell>
                    <cell>product</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^0</m></cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>The pattern in the second column indicates that <m>2^0</m> should yield <q>no factors of 2.</q> But what number makes sense as <q>no factors of 2?</q> To consider this more carefully, let's add one more column to the table showing the values of the powers of two.</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>power</cell>
                    <cell>product</cell>
                    <cell>value</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>16</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^0</m></cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                    <cell><m>?</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>Ah, in the third column, each row's value is half as great as the value above. So the pattern continues if we replace ? with <m>1</m>, then we have <me>2^0 = 1.</me></p>

        <p>Also, multiplication by <m>1</m> has no effect on any number's value, so we could rewrite the second column of the table like so:</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>power</cell>
                    <cell>product</cell>
                    <cell>value</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>16</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2^0</m></cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>Now the numerical meaning of <q>no factors of 2</q> is more clear. <q>No factors of 2</q> have the same effect as multiplying by <m>1</m>. Mathematically, we can read the expression <m>2^0</m> as <q>zero factors of 2.</q> Multiplying by zero factors of any number has the same effect as not multiplying at all, or as multiplication by <m>1</m>.</p>

        <p>There's more to think about here (like what about negative exponents?) but for now, we'll settle for the <term>Zero Exponent Rule</term>, for any real number <m>a</m>, <me>a^0 = 1.</me></p>

