    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Sums and Powers? No Rules!</title>

        <p>Have you noticed that there are no exponent rules involving sums and powers? Let's consider what happens if we replace a product with a sum in one of the exponent rules.</p>

        <p>The Product Rule for exponents encodes the concept that whole number exponents are shorthand for repeated multiplication in a formula: <m>a^n \cdot a^m = a^{n+m}</m>.</p>

        <p>If we rewrite the left side of the Product Rule as a sum, we have <m>a^n + a^m</m>. Now and then, a person who's memorized the exponent rules without thinking about how they work will try to simplify <m>a^n + a^m</m> as follows: 
            <me>a^n + a^m = a^{n+m}</me> 
        This <q>Addition Rule</q> looks a lot like the Product Rule, but does it work? We can check by letting <m>a = 2</m>, <m>n = 3</m>, and <m>m = 4</m> and evaluating both sides of the equation:
            <md><mrow>a^n + a^m \amp= a^{n+m}</mrow>
                <mrow>2^3 + 2^4 \amp= 2^{3+4}</mrow>
                <mrow>24 \amp= 128</mrow></md>
        Yikes, that's not even close. The <q>Addition Rule</q> fails miserably. In fact, without knowing values for <m>a</m>, <m>n</m>, and <m>m</m>, there's no way to simplify the expression <m>a^n + a^m</m>. To see why that's true, let's try substituting values into the expression, first for the base, then for the exponents. If the base <m>a = 5</m> we have <me>5^n + 5^m.</me>
        There's no way to add those values together unless we know the values of the exponents. Alternately, let's substitute values <m>n = 2</m> and <m>m = 3</m> for the exponents. Then <me>a^2 + a^3</me>.
        Without knowing the value of the base, these are not like terms, so we cannot add them together.</p>

        <p>Similar issues arise when we consider other expressions involving sums, differences, and powers.</p>

